<emphasis id="59F7EA9FFFA97F3AFA8AFCFAFE66FC4D" bold="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="12">
Paedogenesis in 
<taxonomicName id="AC834D0EFFA97F3AFB41FCC5FD85FCA1" box="[383,526,863,887]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetranychidae" genus="Tetranychus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="59F7EA9FFFA97F3AFB41FCC5FD85FCA1" bold="true" box="[383,526,863,887]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="12">Tetranychus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and actinotrichid mites
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="23996506FFA97F3AFAA1FC21FD5BF8D4" pageId="10" pageNumber="12" type="description">
<paragraph id="6B3C368DFFA97F3AFAA1FC21FD5BF9FE" blockId="10.[159,762,955,1795]" pageId="10" pageNumber="12">
Identifying the last stase in 
<taxonomicName id="AC834D0EFFA97F3AF819FC21FD20FC05" box="[551,683,955,979]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetranychidae" genus="Tetranychus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="59F7EA9FFFA97F3AF819FC21FD20FC05" box="[551,683,955,979]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="12">Tetranychus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a tritonymph implies that it is paedogenetic. Is this acceptable? Paedogenesis in actinotrichid mites has been reported in various groups, in 
<taxonomicName id="AC834D0EFFA97F3AF849FBBFFF5AFBB6" authorityName="Ewing" authorityYear="1922" class="Arachnida" family="Podapolipidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Podapolipidae</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="0F124B7CFFA97F3AFB33FBD2FE69FBB6" author="Volkonsky M." box="[269,482,1096,1120]" pageId="10" pageNumber="12" pagination="321 - 340" refId="ref9264" refString="Volkonsky M. 1940 - Podapolipus diander n. sp. acarien hOtOrostigmatique parasite du criquet migrateur (Locusta migratoria L.) - Archives Inst. Pasteur AlgOrie, 18: 321 - 340." type="journal article" year="1940">Volkonsky (1940)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName id="AC834D0EFFA97F3AFBC6FBD2FD0FFBB6" authorityName="Oudemans" authorityYear="1937" box="[504,644,1096,1120]" class="Arachnida" family="Pyemotidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pyemotidae</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="0F124B7CFFA97F3AF8FEFBD2FF63FB55" author="Rack G." pageId="10" pageNumber="12" pagination="157 - 174" refId="ref9022" refString="Rack G. 1972 - Pyemotiden an Gramineen in schwedichen landwirtschaftlichen Betrieben. Ein Beitrag zur Entwicklung von Siteroptes graminum (Reuter, 1900) (Acarina, Pyemotidae) - Zool. Anz. Leipzig, 188: 157 - 174." type="journal article" year="1972">Rack (1972)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName id="AC834D0EFFA97F3AFACCFBF1FE10FB55" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1913" box="[242,411,1131,1155]" class="Arachnida" family="Tenuipalpidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tenuipalpidae</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="0F124B7CFFA97F3AFBFBFBF1FDDEFB55" author="Baker E. W." box="[453,597,1131,1155]" pageId="10" pageNumber="12" pagination="355 - 356" refId="ref7319" refString="Baker E. W. 1979 - A note on paedogenesis in Brevipalpus sp. (Acari: Tenuipalpidae), the first such record for a mite - Int. J. Acarol., 5: 355 - 356." type="journal article" year="1979">Baker (1979)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<taxonomicName id="AC834D0EFFA97F3AF8B0FBF1FF42FB70" authorityName="W.E.Leach" authorityYear="1815" class="Arachnida" family="Cheyletidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Cheyletidae</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="0F124B7CFFA97F3AFAC5FB14FE69FB70" author="Atyeo W. T. &amp; Kethley J. B. &amp; POrez T. M." box="[251,482,1166,1190]" pageId="10" pageNumber="12" pagination="125 - 131" refId="ref7218" refString="Atyeo W. T., Kethley J. B., POrez T. M. 1984 - Paedomorphosis in Metacheyletia (Acari: Cheyletidae), with the description of new species - J. med. Entomol., 21: 125 - 131." type="journal article" year="1984">
Atyeo 
<emphasis id="59F7EA9FFFA97F3AFB73FB14FE0EFB70" box="[333,389,1166,1190]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="12">et al.</emphasis>
(1984)
</bibRefCitation>
. The penultimate case is of special interest as 
<taxonomicName id="AC834D0EFFA97F3AFBFDFB2BFDE7FB1F" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1913" box="[451,620,1201,1225]" class="Arachnida" family="Tenuipalpidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tenuipalpidae</taxonomicName>
are part of Tetranychoidea. The missing link is however provided by 
<bibRefCitation id="0F124B7CFFA97F3AFB2EFB6DFE27FAD9" author="Ochoa R." box="[272,428,1271,1295]" pageId="10" pageNumber="12" pagination="117 - 118" refId="ref8844" refString="Ochoa R. 1989 - A note on paedogenesis in Tetranychoidea - Int. J. Acarol., 15: 117 - 118." type="journal article" year="1989">Ochoa (1989)</bibRefCitation>
who reported paedogenetic tritonymphs coexisting with imaginal females in 
<taxonomicName id="AC834D0EFFA97F3AFAA1FAA7FEDDFA83" box="[159,342,1341,1365]" class="Arachnida" family="Tuckerellidae" genus="Tuckerella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="knorri">
<emphasis id="59F7EA9FFFA97F3AFAA1FAA7FEDDFA83" box="[159,342,1341,1365]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="12">Tuckerella knorri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This particular ontogeny is summarized in 
<figureCitation id="F3B82A08FFA97F3AFB12FAFAFE05FAAE" box="[300,398,1376,1400]" captionStart="FIGURE" captionStartId="2.[159,171,913,932]" captionTargetBox="[248,1345,308,877]" captionTargetId="figure-6@2.[242,1346,302,881]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1: Ontogeny in Tetranychoidea (A – H) and other mites (I – J). A – Plesiomorphic ontogeny observed in Tuckerellidae; B – Tetranychidae (traditional interpretation – hypothesis Ho); C – multiple protelattosis in Tetranychidae (hypothesis Hm); D-E-F – metelattosis in Tetranychidae (intervening calyptostasis, hypothesis Hi); G – Tuckerellidae with a paedomorphic tritonymph; H – progenesis in Tetranychidae (hypothesis Hp); I – three calyptostasic nymphs in Ereynetidae (Speleognathinae); J – only four active stases in Astigmata (Psoroptidae). Im: imago; TN: tritonymph; DN: deutonymph; PN: protonymph; Lv: larva; PL: prelarva. Close square: active homostase; Open circle: calyptostase; P: paedomorphic tritonymph; *: reproductive system." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5400176" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5400176/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="12">Fig. 1G</figureCitation>
and links ontogenies A (usually observed in 
<taxonomicName id="AC834D0EFFA97F3AFB51FA19FF5DFA68" authority=", Beard and Walter, 2005" authorityName=", Beard and Walter" authorityYear="2005" class="Arachnida" family="Tuckerellidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Tuckerellidae, 
<bibRefCitation id="0F124B7CFFA97F3AF81EFA19FF5DFA68" author="Beard J. J. &amp; Walter D. E." pageId="10" pageNumber="12" pagination="49 - 60" refId="ref7433" refString="Beard J. J., Walter D. E. 2005 - A new Tuckerella (Prostigmata: Tetranychoidea; Tuckerellidae) from Australia with description of all stages and a discussion of the tritonymphal stage - Acarologia, 45: 49 - 60." type="journal article" year="2005">Beard and Walter, 2005</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
) and H (that of 
<taxonomicName id="AC834D0EFFA97F3AFBA7FA3DFD8BFA68" box="[409,512,1447,1470]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetranychidae" genus="Tetranychus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="urticae">
<emphasis id="59F7EA9FFFA97F3AFBA7FA3DFD8BFA68" box="[409,512,1447,1470]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="12">T. urticae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). A second intermediate case is provided by 
<taxonomicName id="AC834D0EFFA97F3AFBE0FA53FD2BFA37" box="[478,672,1481,1505]" class="Arachnida" family="Tuckerellidae" genus="Tuckerella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saetula">
<emphasis id="59F7EA9FFFA97F3AFBE0FA53FD2BFA37" box="[478,672,1481,1505]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="12">Tuckerella saetula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis id="59F7EA9FFFA97F3AF8DDFA50FD78FA37" box="[739,755,1482,1505]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="12">T</emphasis>
. cf. 
<emphasis id="59F7EA9FFFA97F3AFAF8FA77FED9F9D3" box="[198,338,1517,1541]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="12">pavoniformis</emphasis>
in which the male directly emerges from the deutonymph (Beard and Ochoa, 2010).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6B3C368DFFA97F3AFAFBF9A6FD5BF8D4" blockId="10.[159,762,955,1795]" pageId="10" pageNumber="12">
In the context of the stase theory, 
<bibRefCitation id="0F124B7CFFA97F3AF8B5F9A6FF6DF9A0" author="Hammen" pageId="10" pageNumber="12" pagination="377 - 381" refId="ref8337" refString="Hammen, L. van der. 1975 - L'Ovolution des Acariens et les modLles de l'Ovolution des Arachnides - Acarologia, 15: 377 - 381." type="journal article" year="1975">Hammen (1975)</bibRefCitation>
called alassostasy the variations in the number of stases and the process of loosing a stase during the ontogeny was named meristasy by 
<bibRefCitation id="0F124B7CFFA97F3AF890F939FF62F936" author="AndrO H. M. &amp; Humphries C. J." pageId="10" pageNumber="12" pagination="137 - 187" refId="ref6921" refString="AndrO H. M. 1988 - Age-dependent evolution: from theory to practice - In: Humphries C. J. (Ed.), Ontogeny and systematics. Columbia University Press, New York, USA, pp. 137 - 187." type="book chapter" year="1988">AndrØ (1988)</bibRefCitation>
. The ontogeny in 
<taxonomicName id="AC834D0EFFA97F3AFB83F952FDE8F936" box="[445,611,1736,1760]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetranychidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tetranychidae</taxonomicName>
is thus characterized by the meristasy of the imaginal stase.
</paragraph>
